And um, I was sort of dressed like a Carmen
Miranda type character and I remember I was

00:11:17.550 --> 00:11:18.550
doing the big [short pause].

00:11:18.550 --> 00:11:21.990
And I felt like something might have come
off my hair or something and I was like, oh

00:11:21.990 --> 00:11:23.420
well, [ sings ] Keys to Heaven.

00:11:23.420 --> 00:11:29.940
And I am looking out and there is like people
going [ gasps and covers mouth making noise

00:11:29.940 --> 00:11:32.959
] and this is what I see.

00:11:32.959 --> 00:11:36.050
[ laughter ] and I realize my wig is on the
floor.

00:11:36.050 --> 00:11:38.430
Bald cap, microphone, this.

00:11:38.430 --> 00:11:40.220
just dancing away.

00:11:40.220 --> 00:11:47.190
You know, um, I finished the number completely
bald and then put the wig back on my head

00:11:47.190 --> 00:11:48.649
when it was over.

00:11:48.649 --> 00:11:50.870
It was embarrassing and then three weeks later
I am doing the same show.

00:11:50.870 --> 00:11:53.890
And like at Act II there is this thing that
enters, it's like a bomb.

00:11:53.890 --> 00:11:58.540
This thing that comes out of the audience
and I am waiting at intermissions.

00:11:58.540 --> 00:12:01.640
I can sometimes here the people talk before
I enter because of intermission.

00:12:01.640 --> 00:12:06.940
And I hear, this honest to goodness, this
is like three weeks later, "and then her wig

00:12:06.940 --> 00:12:07.940
fell off and she kept dancing."

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:13.390
I was like, oh, they are talking about me.

00:12:13.390 --> 00:12:15.399
Anyway it was like a p.s. to the most horrifying
moment.

00:12:15.399 --> 00:12:16.809
&gt;&gt; Male audience member #1: Thank you

00:12:16.809 --> 00:12:18.030
&gt;&gt; Lee: Do you want a CD?

00:12:18.030 --> 00:12:21.270
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Oh good, I hope you like it.

00:12:21.270 --> 00:12:22.560
Thank you.

00:12:22.560 --> 00:12:29.040
I love the Dave Matthews Band too, aren't
they amazing?

00:12:29.040 --> 00:12:30.040
[ laughs ]

00:12:30.040 --> 00:12:31.650
&gt;&gt; Female #1: Thank you for coming.

00:12:31.650 --> 00:12:36.730
My husband actually met you, gosh, after you
did Charlie Brown you went to see the first

00:12:36.730 --> 00:12:40.060
regional production of Charlie Brown after
you closed and you sat down with the cast

00:12:40.060 --> 00:12:41.449
and my husband was Charlie Brown.

00:12:41.449 --> 00:12:42.449
&gt;&gt; Kristin: What?

00:12:42.449 --> 00:12:44.830
I remember it, I remember that.

00:12:44.830 --> 00:12:46.670
&gt;&gt; Female #1: So I am here for him and for
me.

00:12:46.670 --> 00:12:47.670
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Well you tell him hi-

00:12:47.670 --> 00:12:51.050
&gt;&gt; Female #1: I will, I'll say "Bob, Kristin
said HI!"

00:12:51.050 --> 00:12:55.069
&gt;&gt; Kristin: hi and that's the only production
I have ever seen of Charlie Brown.

00:12:55.069 --> 00:12:57.380
&gt;&gt; Female #1: Aww, he will be thrilled.

00:12:57.380 --> 00:13:02.180
First of all we love Glee at my house and
thank you for being in it.

00:13:02.180 --> 00:13:06.600
A couple of years ago we took my mother-in-law
to the concert as a surprise at Radio City.

00:13:06.600 --> 00:13:11.040
You weren't there but they were playing the
sound track and a ten year old behind me said

00:13:11.040 --> 00:13:17.649
"Oh my God, I love this song so much!" and
it was you singing One Less Bell to Answer.

00:13:17.649 --> 00:13:18.649
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Are you kidding me?

00:13:18.649 --> 00:13:22.760
&gt;&gt; Female #1: And what struck me in 2009 when
that happened was a ten year old was thrilled

00:13:22.760 --> 00:13:25.650
to hear you sign Burt Bacharach and so I wanted
to ask you.

00:13:25.650 --> 00:13:27.360
It's amazing to me, but,

00:13:27.360 --> 00:13:29.700
&gt;&gt; Kristin: It is amazing to me too.

00:13:29.700 --> 00:13:31.310
I am serious, I'm serious.

00:13:31.310 --> 00:13:33.700
That he would know that music..

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:35.490
&gt;&gt; Female #1: You brought that music back.

00:13:35.490 --> 00:13:39.820
So I wondered who would you like the current
generation of tweens to hear?

00:13:39.820 --> 00:13:43.720
Either through Glee or what music could we
bring back that they need to hear?

00:13:43.720 --> 00:13:46.310
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Ah,, that's a great question.

00:13:46.310 --> 00:13:52.480
You know I, too, love the fact that Glee has
brought, you know in one episode, in the first

00:13:52.480 --> 00:13:57.700
episode I did, I did "Maybe This Time" from
Cabaret.

00:13:57.700 --> 00:14:00.209
I did a Carrie Underwood song called "Last
Name".

00:14:00.209 --> 00:14:06.000
And I did a seventies rock, Heart is the group,
I did "Alone".

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:10.930
And Ryan Murphy, like those three songs completely
different, he has done such a good job at

00:14:10.930 --> 00:14:12.980
bringing all different kinds of music to this
show.

00:14:12.980 --> 00:14:17.880
Which is why it's struck such a cord and why
it makes me happy that a nine year old kid

00:14:17.880 --> 00:14:19.820
go "I love this song!"

00:14:19.820 --> 00:14:24.600
Um, I would love to see, you know, a resurgence
of the thirties.

00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:31.000
I mean, in the thirties and forties music,
that was actually my first record I ever made

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:32.330
was that kind of music.

00:14:32.330 --> 00:14:40.350
Gershwin, Rodgers and Hart, um, you know we
have wonderful composer today but there is

00:14:40.350 --> 00:14:44.820
a sense of innocence, that time that we can
revisit.

00:14:44.820 --> 00:14:48.399
And to make it current again would be amazing.

00:14:48.399 --> 00:14:54.720
But when I think of even you know Cole Porter,
oh gosh, there is too many to mention.

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:56.700
That is probably my favorite era.

00:14:56.700 --> 00:15:00.890
I would love to see that come back more.

00:15:00.890 --> 00:15:03.120
&gt;&gt; Lee: That's a good question.

00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:06.460
So you also won a Tony for "Good Man Charlie
Brown".

00:15:06.460 --> 00:15:08.260
So I have got to put that in there.

00:15:08.260 --> 00:15:09.260
[ laughs ]

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:10.260
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Thank you

00:15:10.260 --> 00:15:11.700
&gt;&gt; Lee: And um, I guess it is kind of a follow
up question for, on the Glee side of things.

00:15:11.700 --> 00:15:12.700
Were you ever in show choir?

00:15:12.700 --> 00:15:14.140
How did you get your start?

00:15:14.140 --> 00:15:15.140
Was--

00:15:15.140 --> 00:15:16.440
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Well my start was in Church.

00:15:16.440 --> 00:15:22.370
I grew up in Broken Arrow, Oklahoma and our
only outlet of performance was either that

00:15:22.370 --> 00:15:23.370
or cheerleading.

00:15:23.370 --> 00:15:28.940
Which I did cause I was like, I can perform,
but I faked the yelling.

00:15:28.940 --> 00:15:33.180
I was a flyer, which is why I smashed my cooter
[ laughs ] I know people have heard this.

00:15:33.180 --> 00:15:37.100
I broke my coccyx cause I was on the top and
somebody got tired and let me down.

00:15:37.100 --> 00:15:42.089
I was in the splits and I was like [ crushing
noise ] with my coccyx, I call it the cooter

00:15:42.089 --> 00:15:43.089
smash.

00:15:43.089 --> 00:15:49.120
But anyway, yeah, the funny thing with me
and cheerleading was I faked yelling cause

00:15:49.120 --> 00:15:51.820
I didn't want to hurt my voice.

00:15:51.820 --> 00:15:54.890
I would be like [ pause ] I did it.

00:15:54.890 --> 00:15:58.402
This one girl, who will remain nameless, was
like "You're faking it!" and I was like "I

00:15:58.402 --> 00:15:59.470
know I am!"

00:15:59.470 --> 00:16:06.020
But we didn't have show choir but what we
did have, which has made me even as nerdy

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:12.019
as you can get, we had Madrigals.

00:16:12.019 --> 00:16:14.470
[ laughs ] Yes, and of course I was the leader
of the madrigals.

00:16:14.470 --> 00:16:18.880
I loved madrigals cause you had to audition
and of course it was like me, auditioning,

00:16:18.880 --> 00:16:20.519
no body else.

00:16:20.519 --> 00:16:22.480
But that holds a special place in my heart.

00:16:22.480 --> 00:16:28.360
I was a big fan of the King Singers, this
madrigal group and, um, yeah, so I was in

00:16:28.360 --> 00:16:34.070
madrigals, I did the choirs concerts, I did
the drama club, and I was a silent cheerleader

00:16:34.070 --> 00:16:37.550
[ laughs ] and I sang at rodeos.

00:16:37.550 --> 00:16:42.670
I sang at anything I could because that was
the only outlet I had.

00:16:42.670 --> 00:16:46.260
&gt;&gt; Lee: Well you certainly had a great career
ever since then.

00:16:46.260 --> 00:16:51.029
And I also heard that ABC picked up a show
called "Good Christian Belles" is coming out

00:16:51.029 --> 00:16:52.029
as well.

00:16:52.029 --> 00:16:53.029
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Yeah, Good Christian Belles

00:16:53.029 --> 00:16:55.680
&gt;&gt; Lee: I caught a little tidbit online and
I know now necessarily you are not supposed

00:16:55.680 --> 00:16:59.079
to believe everything you read, or see online,
although someone did mention to me that you

00:16:59.079 --> 00:17:00.560
said you gotta sing from your cooter.

00:17:00.560 --> 00:17:04.250
Now that we are on the subject, is that true
and how does that work?

00:17:04.250 --> 00:17:07.039
I'm asking too many questions, umm.

00:17:07.039 --> 00:17:10.769
&gt;&gt; Kristin: I can tell you later, Lee!
[ laughter ]

00:17:10.769 --> 00:17:15.480
&gt;&gt; Lee: Um so I heard, um, yeah, I am going
to a completely different subject.

00:17:15.480 --> 00:17:19.609
So the ABC show had a different name of the
pilot, is that true?

00:17:19.609 --> 00:17:21.159
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Yeah, Good Christian rhymes with
witches.

00:17:21.159 --> 00:17:22.159
&gt;&gt; Lee: Um, OHH

00:17:22.159 --> 00:17:28.179
&gt;&gt; Kristin: But it was based on a book that
Kim Gatlin wrote out of Dallas, a wonderful

00:17:28.179 --> 00:17:29.249
writer, very funny.

00:17:29.249 --> 00:17:35.230
It was basically her experience about getting
divorced and moving back from a big city to

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:40.399
Dallas and what she went through with the
girls that she grew up with and how they accepted

00:17:40.399 --> 00:17:41.399
her.

00:17:41.399 --> 00:17:47.679
It is really less about religion and more
about relationships, which is very fun.

00:17:47.679 --> 00:17:52.510
It's funny, I would never do anything that
made fun of anyone's religion.

00:17:52.510 --> 00:17:57.210
So um, there is a difference in making fun
of and having fun with and I think that's

00:17:57.210 --> 00:17:58.330
what he did so well.

00:17:58.330 --> 00:18:02.160
Bobby Harling, who wrote Steele Magnolias
and certainly knows how to write women, wrote

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:03.160
it.

00:18:03.160 --> 00:18:08.250
We have Annie Potts, Jennifer Aspen, Marisol
Nichols, Leslie Bibb and Miriam Shor, some

00:18:08.250 --> 00:18:11.039
of you may know from Hedwig here in New York.

00:18:11.039 --> 00:18:13.570
I must say, I am really proud of it.

00:18:13.570 --> 00:18:20.299
We are in the middle of shooting right now
so I've taken just one week off to talk about

00:18:20.299 --> 00:18:22.609
my record and I'll go on tour when we wrap.

00:18:22.609 --> 00:18:25.809
But we are doing ten episodes then we will
get our air date soon.

00:18:25.809 --> 00:18:29.280
&gt;&gt;Lee: I don't see how you do it all, first
of all.

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:30.280
&gt;&gt; Kristin: I have no life.

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:32.249
&gt;&gt; Lee: I had a question; "What do you do
with your free time?"

00:18:32.249 --> 00:18:34.079
I was like, scratch that off the list.

00:18:34.079 --> 00:18:39.839
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Here is what I do; Hillbilly Handfishing,
Dance Moms, Real Housewives of New Jersey,

00:18:39.839 --> 00:18:46.480
I mean it's mindless because sometimes I just
need to just turn off my brain.

00:18:46.480 --> 00:18:49.260
You guys understand this, you just need to
turn off your brain sometimes, so what better

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:50.460
way than reality TV.

00:18:50.460 --> 00:18:53.609
[laughter]
&gt;&gt; Lee: Those really seem to do the trick.

00:18:53.609 --> 00:18:55.049
&gt;&gt; Kristin: [ laughs ] No kidding.

00:18:55.049 --> 00:18:58.360
&gt;&gt; Lee: Well I guess we can go to another
live question, and give another CD here.

00:18:58.360 --> 00:19:02.179
&gt;&gt; Male #2: Ah, So clearly so much for your
art has to do with music and singing, right,

00:19:02.179 --> 00:19:04.890
with all of your Broadway and your record
and everything.

00:19:04.890 --> 00:19:09.650
And then you did this very sort of straight
role, comedic, but on a drama on the West

00:19:09.650 --> 00:19:11.840
Wing, right, so what was it like doing that?

00:19:11.840 --> 00:19:13.169
What made you decide you wanted to do that?

00:19:13.169 --> 00:19:15.519
&gt;&gt;Kristin: Um, Thank you for asking that question.

00:19:15.519 --> 00:19:21.570
I loved the West Wing but I had been offered
this show and then I had been offered Wicked

00:19:21.570 --> 00:19:25.429
so I had to decide which one I was going to
do and I took Wicked.

00:19:25.429 --> 00:19:28.679
[ applause and cheers ]
&gt;&gt;Lee: Thank-you

00:19:28.679 --> 00:19:32.559
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Kristin: And I think it might have been

00:19:32.559 --> 00:19:33.570
the right decision.

00:19:33.570 --> 00:19:39.059
And then Aaron Sorkin, the creator of West
Wing, had left the show and John Wells took

00:19:39.059 --> 00:19:43.559
over, another amazing show runner and writer,
creator in his own right.

00:19:43.559 --> 00:19:49.639
He had asked me to come on as Annabeth Schott,
and Annabeth was the Deputy Press Secretary

00:19:49.639 --> 00:19:51.029
getting into everybody.

00:19:51.029 --> 00:19:57.779
First in line Richard Schiff's character 'Toby'
to become, first in line to become Press Secretary

00:19:57.779 --> 00:20:02.480
when Allison Janney's character stepped into
a new part.

00:20:02.480 --> 00:20:06.889
And I was really nervous because I am not
really political, like I should never talk

00:20:06.889 --> 00:20:13.049
politics because I would live with my foot
would just be hanging out of my mouth.

00:20:13.049 --> 00:20:15.009
But I learned a lot.

00:20:15.009 --> 00:20:21.879
I learned a lot about different countries
and how they did things.

00:20:21.879 --> 00:20:25.119
Martin Sheen is, gosh, he taught me a lot.

00:20:25.119 --> 00:20:29.440
Everybody on that show was so knowledgeable
in this particular area and I can see why

00:20:29.440 --> 00:20:32.149
because you kind of have to get there because
you are talking about it so much.

00:20:32.149 --> 00:20:37.799
I would get these monologues about Uzbekistan,
this long, and I would be like "Is that by

00:20:37.799 --> 00:20:39.409
Prada, Prada, is that a leather?"

00:20:39.409 --> 00:20:41.909
[laughter]
Anyway but I learned.

00:20:41.909 --> 00:20:47.999
My point is I learned so much and I grew a
lot as an artist.

00:20:47.999 --> 00:20:54.320
Precisely why I took the part, is what you
said, I wanted to do something in a world

00:20:54.320 --> 00:20:56.159
that people might not put me in.

00:20:56.159 --> 00:21:00.759
And it worked out, I was supposed to do three
episodes and I did two seasons.

00:21:00.759 --> 00:21:03.789
So, I loved it, I loved it.

00:21:03.789 --> 00:21:04.789
Thank you.

00:21:04.789 --> 00:21:06.390
&gt;&gt; Lee: Here's your CD.

00:21:06.390 --> 00:21:07.499
Also there is two..

00:21:07.499 --> 00:21:08.499
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Nice to meet you.

00:21:08.499 --> 00:21:09.499
&gt;&gt; Lee: two questions.

00:21:09.499 --> 00:21:14.134
We are going to save the last CD for you,
young lady, but one second and we will come

00:21:14.134 --> 00:21:15.134
back to you.

00:21:15.134 --> 00:21:19.239
Theirs is two questions in the Dory are kind
of related.

00:21:19.239 --> 00:21:23.789
One of them is; Was there ever a point in
your career where you almost, or you felt

00:21:23.789 --> 00:21:27.919
like you almost gave up, or you were just
having a tough time?

00:21:27.919 --> 00:21:33.149
And the other related question is; What advice
would you give to aspiring actors?

00:21:33.149 --> 00:21:35.079
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Well it is related.

00:21:35.079 --> 00:21:36.079
&gt;&gt; Lee: Or artist.

00:21:36.079 --> 00:21:39.710
&gt;&gt; Kristin: I am going to answer the second
half first.

00:21:39.710 --> 00:21:43.529
I've heard, I have said this many times, people
have heard me answer this question before

00:21:43.529 --> 00:21:50.349
and I never have to think about it because
I know what the answer is.

00:21:50.349 --> 00:21:56.609
This life, career, is so rewarding but if
you can see yourself doing anything else and

00:21:56.609 --> 00:21:59.820
being happy then you should do it.

00:21:59.820 --> 00:22:03.289
Because this, this can be hard.

00:22:03.289 --> 00:22:08.119
There is a lot of sacrifice and a lot of challenge
and you are selling yourself.

00:22:08.119 --> 00:22:12.749
It is very hard not to take things personally,
no matter what level you are you get constant

00:22:12.749 --> 00:22:14.249
rejection, it doesn't matter.

00:22:14.249 --> 00:22:18.759
I was sitting in an audition many years ago
and a very famous academy award winner was

00:22:18.759 --> 00:22:21.190
sitting next to me and she was auditioning
for the mother part.

00:22:21.190 --> 00:22:25.539
And I said; "Why are you here?" and I think
you have and Academy A-- I worship you!" and

00:22:25.539 --> 00:22:26.830
she goes "I'm here to audition."

00:22:26.830 --> 00:22:32.359
Just because you get an award doesn't mean
it's over.

00:22:32.359 --> 00:22:39.350
In a way it's more risk involved, you know,
microscope is really there.

00:22:39.350 --> 00:22:45.970
So that being said, if you can't see yourself
doing anything else and being happy then you

00:22:45.970 --> 00:22:48.220
should go for it.

00:22:48.220 --> 00:22:56.039
Because it is the greatest gift to be able
to do what you love and I know because I get

00:22:56.039 --> 00:22:58.409
to do what I love.

00:22:58.409 --> 00:23:03.900
And, um, not everybody can say that and I
am very lucky.

00:23:03.900 --> 00:23:12.070
And it has been hard, there have been times
where I have been [pause] low, I get depressed,

00:23:12.070 --> 00:23:15.849
there is this perception about me that I am
happy all the time.

00:23:15.849 --> 00:23:19.359
I wake up "I'm going to get ready now!

00:23:19.359 --> 00:23:22.879
I'm going to put on my shoes!"
[laughter]

00:23:22.879 --> 00:23:29.210
Umm you know, they say that comedians are
actually very tortured people.

00:23:29.210 --> 00:23:33.580
[giggles] That comedy comes through drama,
it's just sped up.

00:23:33.580 --> 00:23:39.929
Um, and I can understand that, but am I basically
a happy person, Yes.

00:23:39.929 --> 00:23:43.599
I have a lot to be thankful for.

00:23:43.599 --> 00:23:46.080
I have a healthy family.

00:23:46.080 --> 00:23:47.429
I have an awesome pet that I love so much.

00:23:47.429 --> 00:24:01.629
I have great friends, my mom and dad love
m;, they gave me the gift of self esteem.

00:24:01.629 --> 00:24:07.899
And I love it; I love it, but it is hard,
it's hard.

00:24:07.899 --> 00:24:09.439
&gt;&gt; Lee: sounds like good words to live by

00:24:09.439 --> 00:24:10.509
&gt;&gt; Kristin: It is right?

00:24:10.509 --> 00:24:13.360
&gt;&gt; Lee: Someone gave me similar advice, don't
write a song unless you have to.

00:24:13.360 --> 00:24:14.360
&gt;&gt; Kristin: That's great!

00:24:14.360 --> 00:24:16.169
&gt;&gt; Lee: You have to have that passion behind
it and it's

00:24:16.169 --> 00:24:17.169
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Yeah, you do!

00:24:17.169 --> 00:24:18.169
If you have something to say, say it!

00:24:18.169 --> 00:24:22.009
&gt;&gt; Lee: Do you want to go for another live
question?

00:24:22.009 --> 00:24:28.639
&gt;&gt; Female #2: Do you have any advice for people
looking to get into theatre?

00:24:28.639 --> 00:24:34.820
&gt;&gt; Kristin: Well I definitely say, when I
was nineteen before I went to OCU.

00:24:34.820 --> 00:24:38.610
I went to Oklahoma City University for music.

00:24:38.610 --> 00:24:43.500
My father, I had auditioned for Opryland for
the summer.

00:24:43.500 --> 00:24:47.259
I love Opryland, they have put out a mall,
which I love malls, but I am really mad at

00:24:47.259 --> 00:24:55.629
that mall because it took the best music place
in the world to me.

00:24:55.629 --> 00:25:02.049
Um, I auditioned, got into a show called 'Way
Out West' and then I had to go back to school.

00:25:02.049 --> 00:25:04.029
And my dad said "You are going to go back
to school."

00:25:04.029 --> 00:25:07.750
And I was like "NO, I was going to, I'm actually
going to stay in Nashville, I'm going to work

00:25:07.750 --> 00:25:09.610
in Opryland for the rest of my life."

00:25:09.610 --> 00:25:11.789
And he says "No, you're going to go."

00:25:11.789 --> 00:25:16.080
And I said "That's sweet of you, but thank
you [ laughs ] I am going to go ahead and

00:25:16.080 --> 00:25:17.080
stay here."

00:25:17.080 --> 00:25:19.119
And he's like "I'm coming to get you now."

00:25:19.119 --> 00:25:20.119
And took me back.

00:25:20.119 --> 00:25:22.429
And thought I went kicking and screaming.

00:25:22.429 --> 00:25:26.019
I am so thankful that I had my education,
that I had a higher education.

00:25:26.019 --> 00:25:31.219
It gave me an opportunity to hone my craft,
which I still work on.

00:25:31.219 --> 00:25:38.379
It gave me an opportunity to experience a
little bit of life on my own without the roof,

00:25:38.379 --> 00:25:41.059
of being under the roof of my parents.

00:25:41.059 --> 00:25:45.340
It gave me opportunities to screw up and see
what that feels like by myself.

00:25:45.340 --> 00:25:50.739
It gave me opportunities to win and see what
that felt like, so I grew up a lot.

00:25:50.739 --> 00:25:57.159
Um, so I would say New York, and LA and Nashville
and all these other awesome places to work

00:25:57.159 --> 00:25:59.919
and perform are always going to be there.

00:25:59.919 --> 00:26:07.450
You have your whole life, so as much training,
cause there are so many talented people out

00:26:07.450 --> 00:26:08.450
there.

00:26:08.450 --> 00:26:12.399
It just gives you an edge up if you have the
skill to back the craft.

00:26:12.399 --> 00:26:18.609
So I would say, educate, learn, take class,
whatever that means for you.

00:26:18.609 --> 00:26:20.629
That's the best advice I can give.

00:26:20.629 --> 00:26:24.169
And enjoy it, have fun!

00:26:24.169 --> 00:26:25.950
You're welcome.

00:26:25.950 --> 00:26:28.090
I hope you like my record.

00:26:28.090 --> 00:26:29.090
[ laughs ]

