But after you mentioning Nashville.

00:31:54.879 --> 00:31:57.099
&gt;&gt; Kristin: But they have such good food.

00:31:57.099 --> 00:31:59.019
&gt;&gt; Lee: There is good food there, there is
good food.

00:31:59.019 --> 00:32:00.019
&gt;&gt; Kristin: I know.

00:32:00.019 --> 00:32:01.789
&gt;&gt; Lee: So how was that for you?

00:32:01.789 --> 00:32:03.059
Was it a great experience?

00:32:03.059 --> 00:32:06.329
Do you feel like it was kind of referring
to something familiar?

00:32:06.329 --> 00:32:12.750
&gt;&gt; Kristin: I mean, I grew up in a southern
state and I grew up singing and hearing that

00:32:12.750 --> 00:32:13.750
kinds of music.

00:32:13.750 --> 00:32:19.039
You know a lot of people on Broadway grew
up listening to cast albums and going to Broadway

00:32:19.039 --> 00:32:21.599
shoes, or tours and we didn't have that in
Broken Arrow.

00:32:21.599 --> 00:32:25.000
We had cast albums and I did like Les Mis
and the main ones.

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:31.909
But I had never heard of, like, certain shows
so I was into country music and gospel music.

00:32:31.909 --> 00:32:37.450
That was my whole thing so when I went to
do Opryland I feel in love with Nashville

00:32:37.450 --> 00:32:41.309
and I always said 'One day I would be back."

00:32:41.309 --> 00:32:48.509
And I'm twenty years later, um, back in Nashville
recording this record.

00:32:48.509 --> 00:32:53.179
Someone asked me the other day "Why country,
why now?"

00:32:53.179 --> 00:32:55.320
[ laughs ]
I understood the question cause that is not

00:32:55.320 --> 00:33:02.799
what I am known for, but since I was this
big, and I am now only this big [laughs ] since

00:33:02.799 --> 00:33:05.989
this big I wanted to make an album like this.

00:33:05.989 --> 00:33:15.859
So I am thrilled to put this country-pop feel
into the world and let people know how I grew

00:33:15.859 --> 00:33:20.759
up singing and I co-wrote a couple of the
songs so I am putting myself out there as

00:33:20.759 --> 00:33:22.029
a songwriter, too.

00:33:22.029 --> 00:33:26.369
Which is very scary, um and it's scary to
release an album like this cause you don't

00:33:26.369 --> 00:33:28.120
know if it will be accepted, you know.

00:33:28.120 --> 00:33:33.929
But I know that the product, I am so proud
of the things I got to say, which is you get

00:33:33.929 --> 00:33:35.789
to do that when you get to make a record.

00:33:35.789 --> 00:33:42.320
It's about what you have to say, so, um, Bob
Ezrin who did Pink Floyd's 'The Wall' and

00:33:42.320 --> 00:33:44.989
Alice Cooper and you name it, he was my producer.

00:33:44.989 --> 00:33:50.599
I had great songwriters, the best musicians
in Nashville and I just loved my time there.

00:33:50.599 --> 00:33:53.369
My jeans were so tight when I left cause I
was like "meat and three".

00:33:53.369 --> 00:33:58.370
They have this thing there like in Oklahoma
too like, ribs or brisket and you get three

00:33:58.370 --> 00:33:59.370
sides.

00:33:59.370 --> 00:34:01.239
You can pick macaroni and cheese,
&gt;&gt;Lee: okra

00:34:01.239 --> 00:34:06.209
&gt;&gt;Kristin: fried okra, I mean it was a smörgåsbord
; it was a festival of eating every day.

00:34:06.209 --> 00:34:10.149
I loved it so much, um, yeah, I loved Nashville.

00:34:10.149 --> 00:34:11.149
[ laughs ]

